claim.claim-text:
An internal combustion engine, comprising:
a first cylinder (254; 304) having a first piston (250; 300) and a second piston (252; 302) slidably disposed therein and defining a chamber (268; 326) therebetween;
a first port (264; 314) into the first cylinder;
a second port (266; 316) into the first cylinder axially spaced from the first port;
a first converter (260; 308) operable with the first piston to convert mechanical energy of the first piston to electrical energy and electrical energy to mechanical energy of the first piston;
wherein the first converter is operable:
during an intake stroke (280; 350) to hold the first piston in a position with the first port open while the second piston is moved away from the first piston and maintains occlusion of the second port for drawing reactants through the first port into the chamber;
during a power stroke (284, 354) in which a reaction in the compressed reactants in the chamber drives the first and second piston away from one another, to convert mechanical energy of the first piston into electrical energy and to control the position of the first piston so that the first piston occludes the first port;
during an exhaust stroke (286; 356) to move the first piston toward the second piston while the second port is open, thereby exhausting reaction products from the chamber through the second port.

The internal combustion engine of claim 3, wherein

in a first part of an engine cycle, the first valve is set to connect the first port with the intake path, the second valve is set to connect the second port with the exhaust path and the first converter is operable:
during the intake stroke (350) to hold the first piston in a position with the first port open while the second piston is drawn away from the first piston by the crankshaft and maintains occlusion of the second port for drawing the reactants through the first port into the chamber;
during a compression stroke (352) to move the first piston towards the second pistons while the second piston is moved towards the first piston by the crankshaft, occluding both of the first and second ports and compressing reactants in the chamber;
during the power stroke (354) to convert mechanical energy of the first piston into electrical energy and to control the positions of the first piston so that the first piston continues to occlude the first port while the second piston moves to open the second port and transfers mechanical energy to the crankshaft;
during the exhaust stroke (356), while the second piston remains in a substantially fixed position, to move the first piston toward the second piston, thereby exhausting reaction products from the chamber through the second port; and
in a second part of the engine cycle, the first valve is set to connect the first port with the exhaust path, the second valve is set to connect the second port with the intake path and the first converter is operable:
during a further intake stroke (358) where the second piston remains in a position to hold the second port open, to draw the first piston away from the second piston for drawing the reactants through the second port into the chamber;
during a further compression stroke (360) to move the first piston towards the second piston while the second piston is moved towards the first piston by the crankshaft, occluding both of the first and second ports and compressing reactants in the chamber;
during a further power stroke (362) to convert mechanical energy of the first piston into electrical energy and to control the positions of the first piston so that the first piston moves to open the first port while the second piston continues to occlude the second port and transfers mechanical energy to the crankshaft;
during a further exhaust stroke (364), to maintain the first piston in a substantially fixed position while the second piston is moved by the crankshaft towards the first piston, thereby exhausting reaction products from the chamber through the first port.

The internal combustion engine of claim 5 or claim 6, wherein the first and second converters are operable:
during the intake stroke (280) to hold the first piston in a position with the first port open and to move the second piston away from the first piston while maintaining occlusion of the second port for drawing the reactants through the first port into the chamber;
during a compression stroke (282) to move the first and second pistons together, occluding both of the intake and second ports and compressing reactants in the chamber;
during the power stroke (284) to convert mechanical energy of the first and second pistons, respectively, into electrical energy and to control the positions of the first and second pistons so that the first piston continues to occlude the first port while the second piston moves to open the second port;
during the exhaust stroke (286) to hold the second piston substantially still and to move the first piston toward the second piston, thereby exhausting reaction products from the chamber through the second port; and
during a reset stroke (288), to move the first and second pistons together to occlude the second port and to open the first port.

A method of operating an internal combustion engine including a first cylinder (254; 304) having a first piston (250; 300) and a second piston (252; 302) slidably disposed therein and defining a chamber (268; 326) therebetween, a first port (264; 314) and a second port (266; 316) axially spaced from the first port, a first converter (260; 308) being operable with the first piston to convert mechanical energy of the first piston to electrical energy and electrical energy to mechanical energy of the first piston, the method comprising the first converter:
during an intake stroke (280; 350) holding the first piston in a position with the first port open while the second piston is moved away from the first piston and maintains occlusion of the second port for drawing reactants through the first port into the chamber;
during a power stroke (284, 354) in which a reaction in the compressed reactants in the chamber drives the first and second piston away from one another, converting mechanical energy of the first piston into electrical energy and controlling the position of the first piston so that the first piston occludes the first port;
during an exhaust stroke (286, 356) moving the first piston toward the second piston while the second port is open, thereby exhausting reaction products from the chamber through the second port.

The method of claim 12, wherein the internal combustion engine further comprises a first valve (318) configured to switch the first port from connection with an intake path (322) to connection with an exhaust path (324), a second valve (320) configured to switch the second port from connection with an exhaust path (324) to connection with an intake path (322) and a crankshaft (310) connected to the second piston (302), the method comprising:
in a first part of an engine cycle setting the first valve is set to connect the first port with the intake path and setting the second valve to connect the second port with the exhaust path and the first converter:
during the intake stroke (350) holding the first piston in a position with the first port open while the second piston is drawn away from the first piston by the crankshaft and maintains occlusion of the second port for drawing the reactants through the first port into the chamber;
during a compression stroke (352) moving the first piston towards the second piston while the second piston is moved towards the first piston by the crankshaft, occluding both of the first and second ports and compressing reactants in the chamber;
during the power stroke (354) converting mechanical energy of the first piston into electrical energy and controlling the positions of the first piston so that the first piston continues to occlude the first port while the second piston moves to open the second port and transfers mechanical energy to the crankshaft;
during the exhaust stroke (356), while the second piston remains in a substantially fixed position, moving the first piston toward the second piston, thereby exhausting reaction products from the chamber through the second port; and
in a second part of the engine cycle, setting the first valve to connect the first port with the exhaust path, setting the second valve to connect the second port with the intake path and the first converter:
during a further intake stroke (358) where the second piston remains in a position to hold the second port open, drawing the first piston away from the second piston for drawing the reactants through the second port into the chamber;
during a further compression stroke (360) moving the first piston towards the second piston while the second piston is moved towards the first piston by the crankshaft, occluding both of the first and second ports and compressing reactants in the chamber;
during a further power stroke (362) converting mechanical energy of the first piston into electrical energy and controlling the position of the first piston so that the first piston moves to open the first port while the second piston continues to occlude the second port and transfers mechanical energy to the crankshaft;
during a further exhaust stroke (364), maintaining the first piston in a substantially fixed position while the second piston is moved by the crankshaft towards the first piston, thereby exhausting reaction products from the chamber through the first port.

The method of claim 12, wherein the internal combustion engine further comprises a second converter (262) operable with the second piston to convert mechanical energy of the second piston to electrical energy and electrical energy to mechanical energy of the second piston, wherein the first and second converters are either separate converters or are electrically coupled to form a common converter, the method comprising the first and second converters:
during the intake stroke (280), holding the first piston in a position with the first port open and moving the second piston away from the first piston while maintaining occlusion of the second port for drawing the reactants through the first port into the chamber;
during a compression stroke (282) moving the first and second pistons together, occluding both of the intake and second ports and compressing reactants in the chamber;
during the power stroke (284) converting mechanical energy of the first and second pistons, respectively, into electrical energy and controlling the positions of the first and second pistons so that the first piston continues to occlude the first port while the second piston moves to open the second port;
during the exhaust stroke (286) holding the second piston substantially still and moving the first piston toward the second piston, thereby exhausting reaction products from the chamber through the second port; and
during a reset stroke (288), moving the first and second pistons together to occlude the second port and to open the first port.
